}\pard \sl-291 \tx50 \tqr \tx2488 \fs24 \f0 {\pard \posx4782 \posy3454 \phpg \pvpg \absh-2401 \absw6625 \dxfrtext200 \fs10 \f0 \fs25 \f0 \pard \s4 \posx4782 \posy3454 \phpg \pvpg \absh-2401 \absw6625 \dxfrtext200 \qj \li50 \ri50 \sl-261 \tx50 \tqr \tx6574 In a computer that contains three other computers, it's easy to get confused about whether you mean the main computer case or the individual computers inside. Commodore refers to the inside com\-puters as modes, and that's what we'll do in this book. The main computer we'll refer to as the Commodore 128, or as the C128, for short. The three modes built into it are the C128 mode, the C64 mode, and the \fs23 \f0 \i CP/M \fs25 \f0 \plain \fs25 \lang1033 mode. The earlier computer on which the Commodore 128 was based we'll call the Commodore 64, or the C64, for short.\par 
}\pard \sl-261 \tx50 \tqr \tx6574 \fs24 \f0 {\pard \posx3830 \posy6495 \phpg \pvpg \absh-5253 \absw7959 \dxfrtext200 \fs10 \f0 \fs34 \f0 \pard \s5 \posx3830 \posy6495 \phpg \pvpg \absh-5253 \absw7959 \dxfrtext200 \qc \li50 \ri4697 \sl-363 \tx50 \tqr \tx3261 The Commodore 128:\par 
\fs10 \f0 \fs34 \f0 \pard \s6 \posx3830 \posy6495 \phpg \pvpg \absh-5253 \absw7959 \dxfrtext200 \li58 \ri4231 \sl-363 \tx58 \tqr \tx3727 Three Computers in One\par 
\fs10 \f0 \fs25 \f0 \pard \s7 \posx3830 \posy6495 \phpg \pvpg \absh-5253 \absw7959 \dxfrtext200 \qj \li644 \ri64 \sl-261 \tx644 \tqr \tx7894 The main feature of the Commodore 128\'97what sets it apart from almost every other computer ever manufactured\'97is that it is really three sepa\-rate computers packed into one case. These three computers share the same keyboard, and can share external equipment, like the display screen and disk drives; so that when the C128 is sitting on your desk it may look as if there is only one computer system there. However, buried inside its handsome case there are really three separate computers, as shown some\-what fancifully in Figure 1\_2. What are these three computers, and why did Commodore put them together in one case?\par 
\fs10 \f0 \fs25 \f0 \pard \s8 \posx3830 \posy6495 \phpg \pvpg \absh-5253 \absw7959 \dxfrtext200 \qj \li646 \fi438 \ri50 \sl-261 \tx646 \tx1084 \tqr \tx7908 The first computer hidden inside the Commodore 128 is a faithful copy of an earlier computer: the Commodore 64. Introduced in 1982, the C64 turned out to be one of the most successful home computers of all time, with sales of over three million (and still climbing). The C64 was successful because it offered excellent color graphics and sound, which made it a perfect computer for such applications as education and enter\-tainment. It was also, with its built\_in Microsoft BASIC, easy for users to learn to program, and, most importantly, it was priced below the competition.\par 
}\pard \sl-261 \tx646 \tx1084 \tqr \tx7908 \fs24 \f0 {\pard \posx4435 \posy11748 \phpg \pvpg \absh-812 \absw7353 \dxfrtext200 \fs10 \f0 \fs25 \f0 \pard \s9 \posx4435 \posy11748 \phpg \pvpg \absh-812 \absw7353 \dxfrtext200 \qj \li50 \fi438 \ri50 \sl-263 \tx50 \tx488 \tqr \tx7302 Because the Commodore 64 was so successful, a large software in\-dustry grew up to support it. Today there are more than six thousand programs which run on the C64, with new ones being written every day.\par 
