\fs10 \f0 \fs25 \f0 \pard \s3 \posx3911 \posy1513 \phpg \pvpg \absh-2916 \absw7363 \dxfrtext200 \qj \li50 \fi443 \ri50 \sl-260 \tx50 \tx493 \tqr \tx7312 As we noted earlier, these two computers\_within\_a\_computer are re\-ferred to as modes: the C64 mode, which lets the Commodore 128 emulate a Commodore 64; and the C128 mode, which is an entirely new computer with many enhancements and improvements over the C64. In addition to the C64 and C128 modes, Commodore added a third mode: the CP/M mode, which turns the Commodore 128 into a serious business computer. We'll describe these modes briefly here, and explore them in more detail in the chapters to come.\par 
}\sect \sectd \linex0 \linemod0 \sbknone \pghsxn11578 \pgwsxn12240 \marglsxn3855 \margrsxn913 \pard \sl-260 \tx50 \tx493 \tqr \tx7312 \fs24 \f0 {\pard \posx4637 \posy4646 \phpg \pvpg \absh-1092 \absw5897 \dxfrtext200 \fs10 \f0 \fs25 \f1 \i \pard \s4 \posx4637 \posy4646 \phpg \pvpg \absh-1092 \absw5897 \dxfrtext200 \li50 \ri50 \sl-260 \tx50 \tqr \tx5846 It is difficult to make a computer better without, at the same time, making it different. Mu will soon see why the Commodore 128 is both\'97a different computer, and a better one.\par 
}\pard \sl-260 \tx50 \tqr \tx5846 \fs24 \f0 {\pard \posx3934 \posy6044 \phpg \pvpg \absh-382 \absw2085 \dxfrtext200 \fs10 \f0 \fs29 \f0 \pard \s5 \posx3934 \posy6044 \phpg \pvpg \absh-382 \absw2085 \dxfrtext200 \li50 \ri50 \sl-327 \tx50 \tqr \tx2034 The C64 Mode\par 
}\pard \sl-327 \tx50 \tqr \tx2034 \fs24 \f0 {\pard \posx3905 \posy6470 \phpg \pvpg \absh-5009 \absw7373 \dxfrtext200 \fs10 \f0 \fs25 \f0 \plain \fs25 \lang1033 \pard \s6 \posx3905 \posy6470 \phpg \pvpg \absh-5009 \absw7373 \dxfrtext200 \qj \li50 \ri50 \sl-261 \tx50 \tqr \tx7322 As we noted, the Commodore 64 featured excellent color graphics and sound; in fact, the most advanced in the industry for a home computer. The color graphics made use of sprites\'97sophisticated, intelligent graph\-ics entities which could be programmed to represent objects like race cars and space ships. These sprites could be told to move anywhere on the screen and they would do so automatically, without slowing the program down. The sound\_generating capability provided amazing versatility for a machine in this price range, including three voices and a wide variety of ways to shape the sound to produce almost any imaginable effect, from musical instruments to space ships to the human voice.\par 
\fs10 \f0 \fs25 \f0 \pard \s7 \posx3905 \posy6470 \phpg \pvpg \absh-5009 \absw7373 \dxfrtext200 \qj \li55 \fi443 \ri60 \sl-260 \tx55 \tx498 \tqr \tx7312 All these features have been retained in the C64 mode of the Com\-modore 128. In fact, in C64 mode the Commodore 128 is almost identical to the old Commodore 64. It will run all the same software. The screen display is the same, the keyboard operates the same way, and the disk drives and other peripherals that worked on the C64 will work the same way on the C128.\par 
