}\pard \sl-312 \tx50 \tqr \tx2739 \fs24 \f0 {\pard \posx2214 \posy8861 \phpg \pvpg \absh-3185 \absw7347 \dxfrtext200 \fs10 \f0 \fs25 \f0 \plain \fs25 \lang1033 \pard \s7 \posx2214 \posy8861 \phpg \pvpg \absh-3185 \absw7347 \dxfrtext200 \qj \li50 \ri50 \sl-261 \tx50 \tqr \tx7296 A numeric keypad (the number keys clustered together as they are on a calculator) is useful for anyone entering large amounts of numeric data, but this feature was lacking on the Commodore 64. Since many Commo\-dore 64 owners spent hours entering machine language programs in the form of long lists of numbers, this feature was often asked for. The Com\-modore 128 provides a full\_featured numeric keypad, built into the com\-\fs25 \f0 \b puter \fs25 \f0 \plain \fs25 \lang1033 on the right side of the keyboard.\par 
